Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.220 --> 00:00:08.880
&gt;&gt;presenter: So, Kevin Kelly is not only one
of the foremost innovators and writers about

00:00:08.880 --> 00:00:16.890
technology, but his personal story is an equally
interesting one. He rode his bike across America

00:00:16.890 --> 00:00:23.320
and back, and wrote a haiku and drew a drawing
for every day of that journey. He spent seven

00:00:23.320 --> 00:00:28.970
years walking across Asia and he published
a beautiful book of his photography from his

00:00:28.970 --> 00:00:35.239
travels, called "Asia Grace." I first met
Kevin when I was five or six, when my dad

00:00:35.239 --> 00:00:41.300
took over the role of editor from him at the
Whole Earth Review and Kevin Kelly was a founding

00:00:41.300 --> 00:00:46.860
executive editor of Wired. He helped design
and launch the WELL, the famous, prototypical,

00:00:46.860 --> 00:00:53.310
virtual community, as well as HotWired, the
first commercial web scene. He is one of the

00:00:53.310 --> 00:00:58.850
founders of the Long Now Foundation and he
also creates and publishes the website Cool

00:00:58.850 --> 00:01:04.530
Tools. He's also a regular contributor to
the New York Times magazine, publishing features

00:01:04.530 --> 00:01:09.650
on digital culture and one of the last ones
was an education issue about homeschooling

00:01:09.650 --> 00:01:16.040
his son and the role that technology played.
His books include "Out of Control," "Rules

00:01:16.040 --> 00:01:21.040
for a New Economy," several editions of the
Whole Earth Catalog and today, he's going

00:01:21.040 --> 00:01:26.690
to be talking his latest book, "What Technology
Wants." So, please help me in welcoming Kevin

00:01:26.690 --> 00:01:28.690
Kelly.

00:01:28.690 --> 00:01:30.680
[applause]

00:01:30.680 --> 00:01:40.260
&gt;&gt;Kevin: Thank you, Mimi. That was great.
It's great to be back here. About six years

00:01:40.260 --> 00:01:47.590
ago, I actually gave a talk in thinking about
this book, in this very same room on the history

00:01:47.590 --> 00:01:54.070
and the future of the scientific method. And
that talk is now two pages in this larger

00:01:54.070 --> 00:01:59.960
book, which is about the long term trends
in technology. And there's lots of things

00:01:59.960 --> 00:02:07.020
that I feel I could talk to you about this
afternoon, but I think, or I could talk about

00:02:07.020 --> 00:02:11.230
the future of media, the future of the Internet
and the Web and those kinds of things; all

00:02:11.230 --> 00:02:15.819
of which you probably know a lot more about
than I do. And I think I'd rather, instead,

00:02:15.819 --> 00:02:26.370
like to step back and talk about what technology
means and where it, where its place in the

00:02:26.370 --> 00:02:35.470
world, where it wants to be in our minds as
we make all this stuff. So, everyday, you

00:02:35.470 --> 00:02:41.341
folks are involved in creating new things
and the problem is we don't really have a

00:02:41.341 --> 00:02:46.830
very good theory about what it is that we're
making. And so, the current idea about technology

00:02:46.830 --> 00:02:51.030
is basically one thing after another. All
right? We produce one thing after another

00:02:51.030 --> 00:02:55.120
and there's no larger framework about whether
these are good things, whether we want more

00:02:55.120 --> 00:03:02.920
of it, where it fits into the cosmos, how
it relates to nature and what I'm trying to

00:03:02.920 --> 00:03:08.780
do is basically, make a first draft for a
theory of technology; so you can think of

00:03:08.780 --> 00:03:18.300
it in those terms. And so, that sounds kind
of really esoteric, but here's a definition

00:03:18.300 --> 00:03:21.730
that most people think about what technology
is, is about anything that was invented after

00:03:21.730 --> 00:03:28.780
you were born; it's all this new stuff, the
stuff that's coming out of labs here. And

00:03:28.780 --> 00:03:32.650
if you're maybe a little more sophisticated,
you might think of it as stuff that doesn't

00:03:32.650 --> 00:03:39.760
work yet and, or maybe it's the stuff that's
in your pockets. Or maybe anything that has

00:03:39.760 --> 00:03:47.730
an on or off switch. And, I think, of course,
all those gadgets and all those things are

00:03:47.730 --> 00:03:52.810
the stuff that technology is, but it's actually
something more than that. We can take two

00:03:52.810 --> 00:04:01.500
pictures, these two artifacts that are approximately
the same size and shape and one of them can

00:04:01.500 --> 00:04:08.550
easily be made by any of us here--not maybe
as well-- and that's the tool of the hammer

00:04:08.550 --> 00:04:15.510
and that's prehistoric. Or the one on the
right, the mouse or the iPhone or whatever

00:04:15.510 --> 00:04:21.560
you wanna look at, that one not only could
not any of us do, but even the group of us

00:04:21.560 --> 00:04:25.110
here could not do. And, in fact, even everyone
in this building could not actually produce

00:04:25.110 --> 00:04:31.889
that. And that's because that device requires
maybe a thousand intermediate technologies

00:04:31.889 --> 00:04:39.550
to create it and maintain it and operate it,
and each of those technologies might, in turn,

00:04:39.550 --> 00:04:44.710
depend on another hundred intermediate technologies.
So, what we have is the technology we have,

00:04:44.710 --> 00:04:51.000
like on the right, is actually representative
of an ecology of technologies. It's a whole

00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:57.860
set of interrelated, interdependent and codependent
artifacts and that that entire ecology, or

00:04:57.860 --> 00:05:01.850
if you can like, if you wanna think of it
as a super organism of technology, is actually

00:05:01.850 --> 00:05:08.130
what I'm most interested in. And to distinguish
that from the individual technologies or artifacts;

00:05:08.130 --> 00:05:16.780
I call that the "technium." So, the technium
is this huge, super hive, super ecology of

00:05:16.780 --> 00:05:20.650
all the technologies that we have as they
are related to each other and codependent

00:05:20.650 --> 00:05:28.240
on each other. And what we know about systems,
that have that degree of complexity, there's

00:05:28.240 --> 00:05:32.981
two things. The one thing that we know about
those kinds of systems is that, first of all,

00:05:32.981 --> 00:05:39.480
they exhibit behaviors that are not present
in any of the parts, ok? So, you can look

00:05:39.480 --> 00:05:44.210
forever into a tin-, into a bee or an ant
and you'll never see the hive or the colony.

00:05:44.210 --> 00:05:52.960
So, that behavior is not present in the individual
components. And so, the pres-, the actual

00:05:52.960 --> 00:05:58.919
behavior, the technium, is not present in
any of the devices; it has a larger system-wide

00:05:58.919 --> 00:06:03.699
behavior. And secondly, those behaviors have
inherent biases and tendencies. That's what

00:06:03.699 --> 00:06:10.560
we know about systems, ok? And the more recursive
circuits there are in this, the more tendencies

00:06:10.560 --> 00:06:16.009
there are, and so, recursive circuit is the
idea here, the infinite loop or recursive

00:06:16.009 --> 00:06:21.360
loop, where we see this in biology. We have
genes. A lot of the genes in our chromosomes

00:06:21.360 --> 00:06:25.010
are turning on other genes; they're not expressing
protein, but they're turning on other genes

00:06:25.010 --> 00:06:28.479
and some of those genes are turning on other
genes, and some of those genes are turning

00:06:28.479 --> 00:06:32.520
on the first genes. And so, you have this
recursive loop. We have technologies that

00:06:32.520 --> 00:06:39.520
make; technology A makes technology B, technology
B makes C, and C is involved in the creation

00:06:39.520 --> 00:06:45.639
of A, so we have recursive loops within the
technium and whenever you have those, you

00:06:45.639 --> 00:06:51.070
have biases, tendencies. And so, when I talk
about what technology wants, what I'm talking

00:06:51.070 --> 00:07:00.740
about is what the technium is biased towards.
So, it's, I don't mean "want" in terms of

00:07:00.740 --> 00:07:08.270
the way in which an intelligence or conscious
being would want, but I mean "want" in the

00:07:08.270 --> 00:07:15.139
way that plants want light. They're leaning
towards light. The tomato plant on your windowsill's

00:07:15.139 --> 00:07:19.560
leaning towards the light; it's not conscious,
it's not intelligent. It has a bias in its

00:07:19.560 --> 00:07:25.759
system, an urge and need, to move towards
light. And so, we have plants that want light

00:07:25.759 --> 00:07:31.789
and that is what the technium has, is certain
wants. And the question I'm asking is, in

00:07:31.789 --> 00:07:39.660
general, what are the biases in the technium?
And I begin, if, going back to plants, because

00:07:39.660 --> 00:07:46.780
my premise is that, in fact, the technium
is an extension coming from us. It's not just

00:07:46.780 --> 00:07:53.550
from our minds, it's also from a biological
past; from our evolutionary past, that the

00:07:53.550 --> 00:07:58.789
technium is actually extending and accelerating
those same forces. And so, I ask what does

00:07:58.789 --> 00:08:05.490
evolution want? Now, I have to say right away
is that there are some evolutionary biologists.

00:08:05.490 --> 00:08:10.580
Among the most prominent was the late Stephen
Jay Gould, who argued very, very forcefully

00:08:10.580 --> 00:08:17.600
that there are no trends in evolution at all;
that it's trendless. That there's no trajectories,

00:08:17.600 --> 00:08:25.380
there's no directions. And that is the orthodoxy
in evolutionary biology right now, but there

00:08:25.380 --> 00:08:30.030
is, there are minority view and there are
other evolutionary biologists and many of

00:08:30.030 --> 00:08:36.810
them young, who actually have more experience
with computational and computer simulations,

00:08:36.810 --> 00:08:42.569
who actually make a different argument and
have evidence to show that there are trends,

00:08:42.569 --> 00:08:47.690
directions, in the long course of evolution.
And, and the foremost of those is the ones

00:08:47.690 --> 00:08:54.870
that we all intuitively feel, which is that
over 3.7 billion years of life that life has

00:08:54.870 --> 00:09:00.500
gotten more complex. Now, the reason why that's
maybe not an obvious trend is, Stephen Jay

00:09:00.500 --> 00:09:04.399
Gould would say, "Well, if you're starting
off simple, you have nowhere else to go but

00:09:04.399 --> 00:09:11.209
more complex." And so, the fact that the leading
edge is getting more complex is trivial; it's

00:09:11.209 --> 00:09:17.170
not important. The question is about the trailing
edge. And so, we can show, in fact, that when

00:09:17.170 --> 00:09:22.249
you have moved along some evolution and you
are somewhat complex, is there any bias in

00:09:22.249 --> 00:09:30.489
which direction you go then? And we can show
that there's a mild drift towards increasing

00:09:30.489 --> 00:09:37.129
complexity, even at the trailing edge of evolution;
say bacterium. So, what does evolution want?

00:09:37.129 --> 00:09:46.600
Well, again, there is a trend. We have evidence
that there is a trend in greater complexity

00:09:46.600 --> 00:09:54.410
over 3.7 billion years of life; that's one
trend. But there's also trends towards more

00:09:54.410 --> 00:09:59.550
diversity; increasing numbers of different
species. And again, that increasing diversity

00:09:59.550 --> 00:10:04.809
happens not just when you're starting off
with simple, but even wants to have some diversity;

00:10:04.809 --> 00:10:13.310
it rarely goes to less diverse. It generally,
on average, goes to more diverse. And we can

00:10:13.310 --> 00:10:18.509
actually make a list of these things including
increasing complexity, increasing diversity,

00:10:18.509 --> 00:10:24.200
increasing specialization. The first cells
are general. There's one kind of cell that

00:10:24.200 --> 00:10:29.720
does everything. Over time, they evolve into
specialties and so we have 250 different cell

00:10:29.720 --> 00:10:35.889
types in our bodies. We can show the number
of cell types increases over time in evolutionary

00:10:35.889 --> 00:10:44.670
history. Increasing mutualism, codependency
on other organisms as for your life, increasing

00:10:44.670 --> 00:10:50.629
ubiquity, increasing mindfulness, sentience.
We see the mind and the kind of learning that

00:10:50.629 --> 00:10:56.779
a brain does and neurons, even happens in
plants. We see it erupting throughout the

00:10:56.779 --> 00:11:03.749
kingdom of life many, many times independently.
There's increasing learning and evolvability,

00:11:03.749 --> 00:11:08.759
which is the ability to evolve and so we forget
the fact that the evolution process itself,

00:11:08.759 --> 00:11:16.279
is not a singular, fixed process, but itself
has evolved in complexity and it actually

00:11:16.279 --> 00:11:23.049
has made things easier to evolve over time.
So, it's actually, organisms can evolve faster,

00:11:23.049 --> 00:11:28.730
quicker and more degrees of freedom now than
they could two billion years ago. So, there

00:11:28.730 --> 00:11:35.170
is actually the evolution of evolvability
over time. And exotropy, which is increasing

00:11:35.170 --> 00:11:41.889
order, increasing self-organization and increasing
structure. So, those are the kinds of things

00:11:41.889 --> 00:11:48.899
that we see and the reason why that's important
is because, I think, one of the most amazing

00:11:48.899 --> 00:11:54.869
discoveries in the last 50 years has been
the realization that the essence of life was

00:11:54.869 --> 00:12:05.769
not water or some vital spirit or some mystical
force in the world, but actually was information.

00:12:05.769 --> 00:12:11.629
We saw that with the discovery of the DNA
code; we can understand that the essence of

00:12:11.629 --> 00:12:15.929
life was actually information processing.
And, of course, that's the essence of technology

00:12:15.929 --> 00:12:23.679
and it wasn't too long ago, for the first
time, that we actually exported Darwinian

00:12:23.679 --> 00:12:31.249
evolution and moved it in to a computational
world and they, for instance, we used it to

00:12:31.249 --> 00:12:41.259
evolve computer code. Microsoft Word has parts
of its code that was evolved and not actually

00:12:41.259 --> 00:12:47.109
programmed by humans. So, we moved evolution
out of biology into computers and at the same

00:12:47.109 --> 00:12:57.179
time, we could take E. coli and assign numbers
to its genetic sequences and in parallel,

00:12:57.179 --> 00:13:02.329
as a proof of concept, used it as a parallel
processing machine to solve a travelling salesman

00:13:02.329 --> 00:13:09.709
program. So, we used the parallel processing
of E. coli genetics to solve a computer program.

00:13:09.709 --> 00:13:16.670
So, we have evolution moving in computers;
we have life and evolution moving from life

00:13:16.670 --> 00:13:22.369
and doing computation, showing that in some
senses, that there's equivalency between life

00:13:22.369 --> 00:13:27.889
and the technium--that the division that we
normally think of them, as a gulf, is not

00:13:27.889 --> 00:13:34.259
there. In fact, there is a continuum between
the two. So, that means that when we look

00:13:34.259 --> 00:13:42.730
at things like this, this 17, 1800s, this
diversity of smoke catchers is almost like

00:13:42.730 --> 00:13:47.079
a museum collection of different species of
butterflies and we see specialization, of

00:13:47.079 --> 00:13:54.189
course, happening in the technium in mechanical
things. We make a computer or a camera, and

00:13:54.189 --> 00:13:58.679
then we might make this specialized underwater
camera and infrared camera and a high-speed

00:13:58.679 --> 00:14:03.649
camera and then we can specialize that to
make a specialized infrared camera, and then

00:14:03.649 --> 00:14:07.499
a specialized infrared underwater camera and
so it goes on and on; that specialization

00:14:07.499 --> 00:14:16.600
is happening. And we can even map, in some
cases, the genealogy of different inventions.

00:14:16.600 --> 00:14:23.809
And I think that's, the parallels are so steep
that, in fact, we might even think of, these

00:14:23.809 --> 00:14:32.949
are the six kingdoms of life: plants, animals,
fungi and three kinds of bacteria. We might

00:14:32.949 --> 00:14:38.189
think of these six kingdoms of life as actually
producing the seventh kingdom, and I think

00:14:38.189 --> 00:14:43.100
of the technium as basically the seventh kingdom
of life because it shares so many of the attributes

00:14:43.100 --> 00:14:47.720
as a system, again, as a technium; not the
individual artifacts, but as a system, it

00:14:47.720 --> 00:14:54.749
exhibits so many of the same self-organizing
forces that life does that we, that I think

00:14:54.749 --> 00:14:59.940
of it as the seventh kingdom of life. So,
when I ask what does technology want, what

00:14:59.940 --> 00:15:05.970
are the biases and the long-term trends in
technology, I get a very similar answer. And

00:15:05.970 --> 00:15:15.879
again, I wanna go back to the idea that "want"
is not conscious, but is real that even unintelligent

00:15:15.879 --> 00:15:21.939
systems can have wants. So, this is the Willow
Garage PD2, I think, robot which has been

00:15:21.939 --> 00:15:30.290
programmed to find its own energy; to recharge
itself. And so, it will roam through its building

00:15:30.290 --> 00:15:36.889
looking for outlets and then takes its tail
plug and it plugs in by itself, it plugs into

00:15:36.889 --> 00:15:42.180
the outlet until its recharged and then it
takes off again. And I had the privilege of

00:15:42.180 --> 00:15:49.350
standing between it and the outlet and it
very definitely wanted energy. You could feel

00:15:49.350 --> 00:15:54.970
it. And it was gonna find it somehow or another
and it was not conscious, it was not aware,

00:15:54.970 --> 00:16:02.959
it was not very intelligent, but it definitely
wanted electricity. And so, if we again ask

00:16:02.959 --> 00:16:07.790
what the technium wants, what it wants is
the same thing. It wants to head towards;

00:16:07.790 --> 00:16:14.160
it's a general bias to drift towards increasing
complexity, increasing diversity, increasing

00:16:14.160 --> 00:16:19.319
specialization, increasing mutualism, ubiquity,
sentience and evolvability, among other things.

00:16:19.319 --> 00:16:26.079
And so, what does that mean? Well, here's
one example of a long-term trend in technology.

00:16:26.079 --> 00:16:33.229
If you take the power density--the energy
density-- of living, of systems that are in

00:16:33.229 --> 00:16:40.799
disequilibrium, like a galaxy, like a star,
even planets with atmosphere life, you find

00:16:40.799 --> 00:16:45.809
that the amount of energy per second per gram,
so erg's per second per gram, flowing through

00:16:45.809 --> 00:16:52.129
this system for the duration of the system
that the highest energy densities are actually

00:16:52.129 --> 00:17:01.139
increasing over astronomical time. And that,
in fact, there's more energy flowing through

00:17:01.139 --> 00:17:11.889
the cells of a sunflower than there is in
the sun over its entire lifespan. And so,

00:17:11.889 --> 00:17:16.500
the most energy dense entity that we know
about in the world is actually the chip in

00:17:16.500 --> 00:17:21.230
your PC, in your computer. In fact, that's
the problem for engineers is that there's

00:17:21.230 --> 00:17:26.630
so much energy flowing through here and it's
so dense that it's near explosion or meltdown.

00:17:26.630 --> 00:17:34.500
I mean, it's incredibly, incredibly energy
dense state and yet we can actually say that

00:17:34.500 --> 00:17:40.731
where its gonna go is actually gonna be even
further in that direction. So, these systems

00:17:40.731 --> 00:17:44.231
have their own agenda of some sort, and the
question is what is the agenda? And one of

00:17:44.231 --> 00:17:47.860
the agendas is, of course, to increase itself.
I did a calculation that most of the power

00:17:47.860 --> 00:17:54.100
in the technium is using to serve the technium
rather than us humans. When you're driving

00:17:54.100 --> 00:17:59.370
your car, three quarters or more of that energy
that you burn is to move the car, not you.

00:17:59.370 --> 00:18:07.380
You're a minor passenger, literally, in this
thing and we have, your car then has a garage,

00:18:07.380 --> 00:18:11.350
which may be needed to be heated as well,
even when you're not there. And so, we have

00:18:11.350 --> 00:18:18.169
this thing in which the technium is trying,
is increasing, at least servicing more of

00:18:18.169 --> 00:18:23.200
itself. It's, there's more technology and
the more technology is, the more it needs.

00:18:23.200 --> 00:18:27.440
So, that's one sense. And the other one, and
another sense of having an agenda would be

00:18:27.440 --> 00:18:33.500
Moore's Law. So, a great question that I tried
to answer was, "Was Moore's Law inevitable?

00:18:33.500 --> 00:18:39.880
Or, is Moore's Law inevitable?" And Gordon
Moore and Carver Mead, who developed this

00:18:39.880 --> 00:18:47.769
in the 60s, and this, of course, is this unwavering
line over decades of research, independent

00:18:47.769 --> 00:18:52.159
of the fact that people are constantly trying
to accelerate it by putting billions into

00:18:52.159 --> 00:18:55.630
a fad or whatever, or trying to ahead of it;
it still doesn't work, it's just very, very

00:18:55.630 --> 00:18:59.779
straight. They believed it was actually just
a self-fulfilling prophecy, but, of course,

00:18:59.779 --> 00:19:07.190
the problem was is that this curve translated
into like, say operations per second, has

00:19:07.190 --> 00:19:15.090
been going on way before they were aware of
it and we see similar kinds of curves in bandwidth,

00:19:15.090 --> 00:19:23.669
storage, DNA sequencing and all these curves
are on the same kind of unwavering, fixed

00:19:23.669 --> 00:19:28.549
slope and they start long before people believed
them, even when they deny they are there,

00:19:28.549 --> 00:19:35.830
and so it's not just self-fulfilling prophecy.
It is built in to the mechanics of physics

00:19:35.830 --> 00:19:41.409
and chemistry and the slope may be something
that depends on the economy, but the fact

00:19:41.409 --> 00:19:50.000
that it's straight does not. And another example
of an agenda is that most inventions throughout

00:19:50.000 --> 00:19:56.519
history and currently now, are independently,
simultaneously invented. There were 23 other

00:19:56.519 --> 00:20:02.520
people who invented light bulbs before Edison.
When Alexander Graham Bell filed the patents

00:20:02.520 --> 00:20:10.129
for the telephone three years, three hours
later, Elisha Gray submitted for his idea

00:20:10.129 --> 00:20:17.450
and neither, and both had been preceded by
an Italian years before. And in every case,

00:20:17.450 --> 00:20:22.720
we, and we even, in places like, I looked
at the studies of work during the Manhattan

00:20:22.720 --> 00:20:29.539
Project, when there was six different groups
working on things that were absolutely separated

00:20:29.539 --> 00:20:36.660
because of secrecy and wartime division. Even
the three groups in the US were on a need

00:20:36.660 --> 00:20:41.039
to know basis and were not aware of the others'
work, they kept very meticulous records, so

00:20:41.039 --> 00:20:48.740
we have absolute proof, laboratory experiments
of people inventing things completely independent

00:20:48.740 --> 00:20:53.710
and coming up with very similar things and
in the near at the same time. So, whenever

00:20:53.710 --> 00:21:01.440
the precursor inventions are in need, or excuse
me, are in place in this ecology, the next

00:21:01.440 --> 00:21:08.770
